Here's a list of all the Git commands we've discussed in this chat, organized by purpose.

# 1. Create a repository

Initialize a Git repository:

```bash
git init
```

---

# 2. Check repository status

See which files have changed:

```bash
git status
```

---

# 3. Stage files

Stage all files:

```bash
git add .
```

Stage one file:

```bash
git add HelloWorld.java
```

---

# 4. Commit changes

Create a commit:

```bash
git commit -m "Initial commit"
```

---

# 5. View commit history

Full history:

```bash
git log
```

Compact history:

```bash
git log --oneline
```

Show the last 3 commits:

```bash
git log -3
```

Show the last 3 commits in one-line format:

```bash
git log --oneline -3
```

Show commits with code changes:

```bash
git log -p
```

Show history as a graph:

```bash
git log --oneline --graph --all
```

Show commits on GitHub that you don't have locally:

```bash
git log main..origin/main
```

Show commits you have locally that haven't been pushed:

```bash
git log origin/main..main
```

---

# 6. Compare code

Compare your local branch with the remote-tracking branch:

```bash
git diff main origin/main
```

---

# 7. Configure remote repository

Add GitHub as a remote:

```bash
git remote add origin https://github.com/<username>/hello-java.git
```

List configured remotes:

```bash
git remote -v
```

---

# 8. Branch commands

Rename the current branch:

```bash
git branch -M main
```

Show local branches:

```bash
git branch
```

---

# 9. Upload and download

Push for the first time:

```bash
git push -u origin main
```

Push later:

```bash
git push
```

Force push (use with caution):

```bash
git push --force origin main
```

Download remote changes only:

```bash
git fetch
```

Download and merge:

```bash
git pull
```

---

# 10. Reset branch

Move branch, keep staged changes:

```bash
git reset --soft <commit-id>
```

Move branch, keep unstaged changes:

```bash
git reset --mixed <commit-id>
```

or

```bash
git reset <commit-id>
```

Move branch and discard changes:

```bash
git reset --hard <commit-id>
```

---

# 11. Revert commits

Undo one commit safely:

```bash
git revert <commit-id>
```

Undo the latest commit:

```bash
git revert HEAD
```

Undo the last three commits:

```bash
git revert HEAD~2..HEAD
```

---

# 12. Useful everyday workflow

```bash
git status
git add .
git commit -m "Describe your changes"
git push
```

---

# 13. Team workflow

```bash
git fetch
git log main..origin/main
git diff main origin/main
git pull
```

---

## Commands you'll use most often

If you're starting with Git, focus on these 15 commands:

| Command                     | Purpose                                  |
| --------------------------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| `git init`                  | Create a Git repository                  |
| `git status`                | Check file status                        |
| `git add .`                 | Stage all changes                        |
| `git commit -m "..."`       | Save a snapshot                          |
| `git log --oneline`         | View commit history                      |
| `git branch`                | List branches                            |
| `git branch -M main`        | Rename current branch                    |
| `git remote add origin ...` | Connect to GitHub                        |
| `git remote -v`             | Show remotes                             |
| `git push -u origin main`   | First push to GitHub                     |
| `git push`                  | Push new commits                         |
| `git fetch`                 | Download remote updates                  |
| `git pull`                  | Download and merge updates               |
| `git diff`                  | Compare file changes                     |
| `git revert <commit>`       | Safely undo a commit in a shared project |

These commands cover most of the Git operations you'll perform in day-to-day development. As you become more comfortable with Git, you can build on this foundation with branching, merging, rebasing, and other advanced workflows.

